<br>
What courts say is that this merely identifies the party that can exercise its discretion, but that it still must act reasonably and in good faith.  "Sole discretion" does not mean that a party can act in bad faith.<br>
<br>
Warning, legal quotation ahead (but I'll keep this one short):<br>
<br>
<i>The  phrase "in her  sole discretion"  does not waive the good  faith  requirement placed upon acts of discretion, but merely limits who makes the decision.</i><br>
<br>
<br>
So, what sort of language is required to waive the good faith requirement, if you can?  This may be limited in some jurisdictions by statute based on the nature of the contract, but in general:<br>
<br>
<i><=52>  The good faith requirement may be waived by the words of the trust but the words are interpreted narrowly. Words found to waive the reasonableness standard are "absolute" or "unlimited" or "uncontrolled" discretion. To the contrary, the words "in  sole  discretion"  do not waive[**11] the good  faith  requirement. </i><br>
<br>
<br>
Of course, this means that Mystic does have great latitude in making decisions about customer accounts.  But it is not unbounded, especially when it has promulgated certain standards of accepted behavior. <br>
<br>
<br>
